d from the United States to forge a fellowship with those workers. Luna examines the entanglements, both intimate and financial, that define their lives. Using the concept of obligar, she delves into the connections that tie sex workers to their families, their clients, their pimps, the missionaries, and the drug dealers-and to the guilt, power, and comfort of faith. Love in the Drug War scrutinizes not only la zona and the people who work to survive there, but also Reynosa itself-including the influences of the United States-adding nuance and new understanding to the current Mexico-US border crisis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChurch work with prostituteszMexicozReynosa (Tamaulipas) 0aChurch work with prostituteszMexicozReynosa (Tamaulipas). 0aDrug trafficxSocial aspectszMexicozReynosa (Tamaulipas) 0aDrug trafficxSocial aspectszMexicozReynosa (Tamaulipas). 0aProstitutionzMexicozReynosa (Tamaulipas) 0aProstitutionzMexicozReynosa (Tamaulipas). 0aReligion and culturezMexicozReynosa (Tamaulipas) 0aReligion and culturezMexicozReynosa (Tamaulipas). 0aSex-oriented businesseszMexicozReynosa (Tamaulipas) 0aSex-oriented businesseszMexicozReynosa (Tamaulipas). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32049540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477320518423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781477320518.jpg  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK